{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609386"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16101"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16101"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.26,0.41,0.17,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55879"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8067"},{"type":"tags","id":"9662"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"},{"type":"tags","id":"10885"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20992"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, infections of the placenta, foetal membranes, and amniotic fluid typically occur through ascending spread from the birth canal. While most cases are caused by bacteria such as Group B \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, certain viruses can also cause significant infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following viruses is most likely to cause ascending infection of the placenta and foetal membranes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Human immunodeficiency virus","Herpes simplex virus","Cytomegalovirus","Human papillomavirus","Hepatitis B virus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely viral cause of ascending infection during pregnancy. It can spread from active genital lesions through the cervix to cause infection of the placenta, membranes, and amniotic fluid, potentially leading to severe neonatal herpes infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other viruses are less likely causes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily spreads through blood and can cross the placenta, but does not typically cause ascending infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes transplacental rather than ascending infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman papillomavirus\u003C/strong\u003E affects the cervix and lower genital tract but rarely causes ascending infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus\u003C/strong\u003E spreads through blood and can transmit vertically, but does not typically cause ascending infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Herpes simplex virus can cause ascending infection during pregnancy, potentially leading to severe neonatal infection.","Most intrauterine infections are bacterial, but HSV is a significant viral cause of ascending genital tract infection during pregnancy."],"references":["Hammad WAB, Konje JC. Herpes simplex virus infection in pregnancy - An update. Eur J Obstet Gynecol Reprod Biol. 2021 Apr;259:38-45. doi: 10.1016/j.ejogrb.2021.01.055. Epub 2021 Feb 4. PMID: 33581405.","James SH, Sheffield JS, Kimberlin DW. Mother-to-Child Transmission of Herpes Simplex Virus. J Pediatric Infect Dis Soc. 2014 Sep;3 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S19-23. doi: 10.1093/jpids/piu050. PMID: 25232472; PMCID: PMC4164179.","Straface G, Selmin A, Zanardo V, De Santis M, Ercoli A, Scambia G. Herpes simplex virus infection in pregnancy. Infect Dis Obstet Gynecol. 2012;2012:385697. doi: 10.1155/2012/385697. Epub 2012 Apr 11. PMID: 22566740; PMCID: PMC3332182.","Straface G, Selmin A, Zanardo V, De Santis M, Ercoli A, Scambia G. Herpes simplex virus infection in pregnancy. Infect Dis Obstet Gynecol. 2012;2012:385697. doi: 10.1155/2012/385697. Epub 2012 Apr 11. PMID: 22566740; PMCID: PMC3332182.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16101"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T23:02:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T23:04:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","l